# Clean Code Principles

## Naming
- Use descriptive, intention-revealing names for variables, functions, and files
- Boolean variables start with `is`, `has`, `should`, `can` (e.g., `isLoading`, `hasDiscount`)
- Event handlers use `handle` prefix (e.g., `handleAddToCart`)
- Functions that return data use `get` or `fetch` prefix
- Constants use UPPER_SNAKE_CASE (e.g., `MAX_CART_ITEMS`, `API_BASE_URL`)

## Constants
- No magic numbers or strings -- extract to named constants
- Keep constants in a dedicated `src/lib/constants.ts` file or colocated with the module

## Functions
- Each function does exactly one thing
- Keep functions under 30 lines; extract helpers if longer
- Prefer pure functions where possible
- Always handle errors explicitly -- never silently catch

## File Structure
- One component per file
- Colocate tests with source files (`Component.tsx` + `Component.test.tsx`)
- Group by feature, not by type, inside `src/`
- Keep imports ordered: external libs > absolute paths > relative paths

## Error Handling

```typescript
// BAD -- silent failure
try { await fetchProducts(); } catch (e) { console.log(e); }

// GOOD -- user-facing error + logging
try {
  await fetchProducts();
} catch (error) {
  console.error('[ProductService] Failed to fetch products:', error);
  throw new Error('Unable to load products. Please try again.');
}
```

## No Debug Code in Commits
- Remove all `console.log` before committing
- Use a proper logger utility if logging is needed
